Goal:
Implement the next minimal domain step from the handoff: persistent topics in SQLite as first-class content groups.

Context:
The project already has:
- Telegram bot foundation
- user/profile persistence
- teacher-student invite/link MVP
- vocabulary persistence (`lexemes`, `learning_items`, `learning_item_translations`)
- minimal training session logic
- homework-first `/start`
- assignments
- assignment by seeded named groups (`weekdays`, `months`, `colors`)

Current limitation:
There is still no real topic model in persistence.
Seeded named groups are only a temporary grouping mechanism and are not first-class runtime entities.

We need to introduce real topics in SQLite and connect them to learning_items, while keeping the implementation minimal.

Feature:
Persistent Topics MVP

Scope:
1. Add SQLite persistence for:
   - `topics`
   - `topic_learning_items`

2. `topics` should be minimal first-class entities:
   - `id`
   - `name` (stable key, unique, e.g. `months`)
   - `title` (human-readable label, e.g. `Месяцы`)
   - optional `created_at` only if it matches current schema style

3. `topic_learning_items` should link topics to learning_items:
   - `topic_id`
   - `learning_item_id`
   - no extra metadata unless absolutely necessary

4. Rework starter vocabulary seeding:
   - seeded groups (`weekdays`, `months`, `colors`) must now be created as real `topics`
   - their learning_items must be linked through `topic_learning_items`
   - do not duplicate content or keep parallel grouping models unless required for migration compatibility

5. Add minimal topic persistence/read helpers:
   - create topic
   - link learning item to topic
   - list topics
   - get learning items for one topic
   - resolve topic by name

6. Rework assignment flow to use real topics as the primary named-group path:
   - `/assign <student_user_id> <topic_name>` should resolve from `topics.name`
   - keep legacy raw-id assignment path if it already exists
   - do not require any new UI beyond the current minimal command flow unless clearly needed

7. Student homework should continue showing human-readable assignment titles.
   - use topic title when assignment is created from a topic unless explicit title handling already exists

8. Keep `/learn` behavior unchanged in this slice unless topic integration is trivial and clearly minimal.
   - Topic-based learner selection is NOT required in this task.

Out of scope:
- lessons
- nested topics
- topic ordering UI
- topic editing UI in Telegram
- topic deletion flows
- FSM
- deep links
- asset playback
- homework type variants
- advanced statistics
- billing
- web app topic management
- broad refactors

Architecture constraints:
- Keep business logic outside Telegram handlers
- Do not turn `bot.py` into a catch-all
- Reuse existing vocabulary/homework modules where reasonable
- Add focused new module(s) only if topics introduce a clearly separate responsibility
- Avoid parallel models for "seed groups" and "topics" unless migration compatibility truly requires it
- Keep the change minimal and product-driven

Data model expectations:
- Topics are first-class persisted entities
- One topic can contain many learning_items
- One learning_item may be linked to multiple topics if needed by the model
- Do not redesign lexeme/learning_item structure

Testing requirements (MANDATORY):
Add focused automated tests for:
- schema creation for `topics` and `topic_learning_items`
- creating and reading topics
- linking learning_items to topics
- resolving topic by name
- seeded topics creation
- assignment creation from a persisted topic
- student-visible assignment title/name when created from topic
- keep tests focused and avoid Telegram runtime dependency where possible

Workflow:
1. architect:
   - propose the smallest design
   - list files to modify
   - list files to add
   - explain why this is the minimal reasonable topic model

2. complexity_guard:
   - reject overengineering
   - reject lesson/nesting/editor creep
   - reject unnecessary abstractions
   - reject missing tests

3. coder:
   - implement only the approved minimal plan
   - add focused tests
   - update requirements.txt only if needed
   - update CHANGELOG.md
   - update context/current_state.md

4. complexity_guard:
   - verify:
     - no catch-all files
     - no duplicate grouping model left without reason
     - tests exist and are focused
     - scope stayed limited to topics MVP

Definition of done:
- `topics` and `topic_learning_items` exist in SQLite
- seeded starter groups are represented as real topics
- assignment by topic name works through persisted topics
- student-facing homework still shows meaningful titles
- tests cover schema, persistence, seeding, and topic-based assignment behavior
- CHANGELOG.md and context/current_state.md are updated